{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EAvFF9qzNKXzqmhU2N3Cyp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about manifest validation logic — parsing JSON and checking for required fields. The failure mode is purely in the validation function. No module handoff needed.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. The manifest can be a fake JSON object passed to a validation function.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No real dependencies needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nMinimum level: **Unit** — validation logic on a parsed manifest object. \n\nThe tricky part is that \"before any code is executed\" means I need to verify not just that validation fails, but that the plugin module never gets imported. Testing the validator alone confirms rejection, but to ensure the loader actually prevents module loading when validation fails, I'd need to test the loader's integration with the module system. So this really needs at least an Integration test to verify the full rejection flow. validation fails, but not that the loader respects the validation result. To test both (rejection + no code execution), we need the loader integrated with a mock module system. This could be Integration.\n\nActually, \"before any code from that plugin is executed\" is the key constraint. If we're just testing the validation function returning an error, that's Unit. But verifying that no module import happens requires the loader. This is Integration — the validator and loader modules interacting.\n\nHmm, but we could test this with mocked/stubbed require/import. If we mock the module loading mechanism and verify it's not called when validation fails — that's Integration-ish but could be done in-process.\n\nI'll say Integration is minimum here — because verifying \"no code executed\" requires the loader to respect validation results, which is a module boundary.\n\nActually wait — let me reconsider. The validation itself is Unit. The \"no code executed\" guarantee could be tested by feeding an invalid manifest to the loader, mocking the require call, and asserting it was never invoked. That's Integration since the validator and loader need to work together, though it can run in-process.\n\nFor the second behavior around dependency ordering, this is clearly Integration — the dependency resolver and execution engine need to interact properly. The bug surfaces at their boundary when the resolved order gets handed to the execution engine. No real filesystem is needed since we can pass fake plugin objects in memory, but we can't mock the pieces separately without missing the ordering issue.\n\nFor cycle detection, the algorithm itself is Unit-testable on a graph structure. But the full behavior — detecting the cycle AND ensuring neither plugin loads — requires the detector and loader wired together. If we're testing just the detection, that's Unit. If we're testing that no code executes after detection, that's Integration.\n\nFor the onLoad hook timing, I need to verify that the module import happens before the hook fires. In Node.js, `require()` or `import()` actually executes the module, so I can mock it and check the call order. The question is whether I need a real module or if mocking the import is sufficient to verify the sequencing.\n\nThe tricky part is that \"executed\" means the module code actually ran and had side effects. To properly test this, I'd need a real module file that sets some state when it loads, then confirm that state exists before onLoad is called. This requires a real file on disk.\n\nFor the test level, creating a temporary file is still using the OS filesystem, but that's typically considered Integration rather than System—it's local, no external services involved. I could set up an Integration test by creating a real plugin module file, running the loader against it, and verifying the hook fires after the import completes.\n\nFor Behavior 5, this is about error isolation in the loader's logic—when one plugin's onLoad throws, the loader should continue initializing others that don't depend on it. I could test this at Unit level by stubbing the plugin hooks, making one throw while others succeed, and verifying the non-dependent plugins still initialize. The tricky part is that \"do not depend on it\" requires checking the dependency graph, which adds complexity to what should be tested.\n\nActually, I'm realizing this sits at the boundary between Unit and Integration. If the loader is a single module handling both error handling and dependency tracking, I could test it in isolation with fake plugins. But since the loader needs to coordinate across multiple plugins and their relationships, I think Integration is the right call—I'm testing the loader's behavior as a whole system with multiple plugins interacting.\n\nMinimum: **Integration**\n\nNow I'm ready to write up the full analysis.\n\nLooking at all five behaviors, they're all Integration tests. Let me verify this makes sense. For the first one about manifest validation, I could split this into a Unit test of the validator itself and an Integration test verifying the full rejection-to-no-execution flow. But the core behavior being tested—that invalid manifests are rejected before any code runs—really requires both the validator and loader working together.\n\nFor behavior 4 about hook invocation timing, I need actual module execution to verify the hook runs after the entry module loads. Mocking require lets me check the call order, but Integration is the right level to confirm the actual execution sequence. I'm satisfied that all five are Integration tests.\n\nNow I'll structure the output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9924,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9924},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ac95191-0b6e-4e40-b352-ca098f9bdad6","uuid":"d81008fa-a37b-47f0-9738-ae69000b61e8"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EAvFF9qzNKXzqmhU2N3Cyp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01V5tA31fvdXZczuBMG8sGna","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior has two inseparable parts — (a) validation rejects the manifest and (b) no module code is executed. Testing the validator in isolation proves (a) but cannot prove (b). Proving (b) requires the loader module to respect the validation result and not invoke require/import. That is a module-boundary interaction: validator → loader. REAL-INFRA: No real filesystem or network needed; the manifest can be a plain in-process object and require() can be stubbed to verify it was never called. MOCK-HIDE: If we only unit-test the validator, a bug where the loader ignores the validation result and loads the module anyway is invisible. REJECTION of System/Agentic: no OS I/O, no AI/ML, no subprocess is needed to reproduce this failure.","test_description":"Wire the manifest validator and the plugin loader together in-process. Provide a manifest object missing a required field (e.g., 'name'). Stub the module-import call (require/dynamic import). Assert the loader returns a rejection error AND that the import stub was never invoked, confirming no plugin code ran.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When plugin A declares a dependency on plugin B, plugin B's onLoad hook is called before plugin A's.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the handoff between the dependency resolver (which computes a topological order) and the hook executor (which iterates that order and calls hooks). A unit test of the resolver alone only verifies the sorted order is correct data; it cannot catch a bug where the executor ignores the order. These two modules must be wired together. REAL-INFRA: No real filesystem or network is needed; plugins can be in-memory stubs with fake onLoad hooks. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing either the resolver or the executor in isolation always passes, hiding the failure. REJECTION of System/Agentic: call ordering is deterministic and requires no real OS resources or AI/ML model.","test_description":"Create two in-memory plugin stubs — plugin A declaring dependency on B, each with an onLoad that appends its name to a shared call-order array. Feed both to the loader. Assert that B's name appears before A's name in the call-order array.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Like behavior 2, this has two parts: cycle detection and the enforcement that neither plugin is loaded. Unit-testing the cycle detector in isolation only verifies it returns a cycle error; it cannot verify the loader honors that result and skips both modules. The failure boundary is the handoff between the cycle-detection algorithm and the loader's execution gate. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network required; manifests are in-memory objects. MOCK-HIDE: A unit test of cycle detection that stubs the loader would pass even if the loader had a bug that proceeded to load one of the plugins anyway. REJECTION of System/Agentic: deterministic algorithm, no real infrastructure.","test_description":"Create two in-memory plugin stubs where A depends on B and B depends on A, each with an onLoad that sets a flag. Pass both to the loader. Assert the loader returns a cycle-error diagnostic naming both plugins AND that neither onLoad flag was set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's onLoad hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure boundary is the sequencing contract between the module-import step and the hook-invocation step inside the loader. A unit test of the hook executor alone cannot verify it waits for the import to complete. The importer and hook executor must be wired together. REAL-INFRA: The 'has been executed' guarantee requires something to observe that the module body ran before onLoad fired. This can be satisfied in-process: a fake module stub that sets a flag when 'required', and an onLoad that reads that flag — no real filesystem or subprocess needed. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the import entirely and asserting call order proves only sequencing of two stubs; it does not catch a bug where the loader starts onLoad before the async import resolves. REJECTION of System: a real file on the real filesystem is not needed — an in-process module stub reproduces the exact failure mode.","test_description":"Create a plugin stub whose 'module' sets an 'imported' flag when the loader invokes the import step, and whose onLoad asserts that the flag is already true when it runs. Pass this stub to the loader. Assert onLoad completes without throwing, confirming the import ran first.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.19,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'Do not depend on it' means the loader must consult the dependency graph when deciding which remaining plugins to skip vs. continue. This ties the error-handling path to the dependency-resolution module. A unit test of the loader's try/catch logic with a completely flat (no-dependency) plugin set would not catch a bug where the loader skips an unrelated plugin that shares no dependency edge with the failing one. REAL-INFRA: No real OS resources needed; all plugins can be in-memory stubs. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the dependency tracker always produces an empty skip-set, masking bugs in the loader's 'skip dependents' traversal. REJECTION of System/Agentic: deterministic error isolation logic, no AI/ML or real infrastructure.","test_description":"Create three in-memory plugin stubs: A (throws in onLoad), B (depends on A, should be skipped), and C (no dependency on A, should proceed). Feed all three to the loader. Assert the loader records an error for A, does not invoke B's onLoad, and does invoke C's onLoad successfully.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9924,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9924},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ac95191-0b6e-4e40-b352-ca098f9bdad6","uuid":"04414427-8cb4-4d31-964c-0e5080d2628c"}
